'''Beroe''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: Βερόη) in [[Greek mythology]] is a nymph of Beirut, the daughter of [[Aphrodite]] and [[Adonis]], and sister of [[Golgos]].<ref>{{cite book | title=[[The Greek Myths]] | publisher=Penguin Books | author=[[Graves, Robert]] | year=1960 | location=London | pages=70 | isbn=9780140171990}}</ref> She was wooed by both [[Dionysus]] and [[Poseidon]], eventually marrying [[Poseidon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Aphrodite family|url=http://www.theoi.com/Olympios/AphroditeFamily.html|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Poseidin's wives|url=http://www.maicar.com/GML/Poseidon.html|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref>
At the birth of Beroe, Hermes acted as the midwife and assisted in the delivery of Beroe then the Virgin Astraia (lady of justice) took the infant Beroe and fed her with the wise breast and told her words of law, feeding her honey and washing her with sacred water.<ref name="theoi">{{cite web|title=Nymphe Beroe|url=http://www.theoi.com/Nymphe/NympheBeroe.html|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref> As she grew up, she was highly regarded as an outstanding beauty and destined to marry Poseidon.<ref name="theoi" /> [[Eros]] struck her twice with arrows of love and a confrontation took place for her love.<ref name="theoi" /> Beroe wore no ornaments or make-up, and she was not vain and never examined herself in the mirror.<ref name="theoi" /> Beroe was a mortal but often her beauty was compared to that of goddesses.<ref name="theoi" />
